. Field offers the first English-language translations of two of the earliest and most important accounts of the king’s life: one composed by Geoffrey of Beaulieu, the king’s long-time Dominican confessor, and the other by William of Chartres, a secular clerk in Louis’s household who eventually joined the Dominican Order himself. Written shortly after Louis’s death, these accounts are rich with details and firsthand observations absent from other works, most notably Jean of Joinville’s well-known narrativeThe introduction by M. Cecilia Gaposchkin and Sean L. Field provides background information on Louis IX and his two biographers, analysis of the historical context of the 1270s, and a thematic introduction to the texts. An appendix traces their manuscript and early printing histories. The Sanctity of Louis IX also features translations of Boniface VIII’s bull canonizing Louis and of three shorter letters associated with the earliest push for his canonization. It also contains the most detailed analysis of these texts, their authors, and their manuscript traditions currently available.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChristian saintsxBiographyxFrance. 0aChristian saintszFrancevBiography. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aField, Larry F.1 aField, Sean L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGaposchkin, M. Cecilia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146914540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801469145423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801469145.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-201